'''Vladimir Petković''' ({{IPA|hr|ʋlǎdimiːr pêtkoʋit͡ɕ}}; born 15 August 1963) is a Bosnian professional [[association football|football]] [[Manager (association football)|manager]] and former [[football player|player]] who is the head coach of the [[Algeria national football team|Algeria national team]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bourebala |first=Mohamed |date=29 February 2024 |title=National team: Bosnian Vladimir Petkovic in as new manager |url=https://www.aps.dz/en/sports/51145-national-team-bosnian-vladimir-petkovic-new-manager |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240303080219/https://www.aps.dz/en/sports/51145-national-team-bosnian-vladimir-petkovic-new-manager |archive-date=3 March 2024 |access-date=29 February 2024 |work=Algeria Press Service |language=en}}</ref> He was previously manager of French side [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]],  the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland national team]], a string of Swiss clubs, Turkish club [[Samsunspor]], and Italian club [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]].

Petković is from [[Sarajevo]], Bosnia and Herzegovina. He holds [[Bosnia and Herzegovina nationality law|Bosnian]], [[Swiss nationality law|Swiss]] and [[Croatian nationality law|Croatian]] passports.<ref>[https://nzzas.nzz.ch/magazin/wer-ist-vladimir-petkovic-auf-spurensuche-in-sarajevo-ld.1628602 ''Wer ist Vladimir Petkovic? Auf Spurensuche in Sarajevo.''] In: ''[[NZZ am Sonntag]]'', 5 June 2021.</ref>

==Early life==
Petković was born in [[Sarajevo]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]], modern-day Bosnia and Herzegovina, in 1963 to a [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Croat]] family.<ref name="thesefootballtimes">{{cite news|title=Vladimir Petković: the migrant who struggled his way to the top of Swiss football|newspaper=[[These Football Times]]|date=3 July 2018 |author=Damir Kulas|url=https://thesefootballtimes.co/2018/07/03/vladimir-petkovic-the-migrant-who-struggled-his-way-to-the-top-of-swiss-football/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200719023251/https://thesefootballtimes.co/2018/07/03/vladimir-petkovic-the-migrant-who-struggled-his-way-to-the-top-of-swiss-football/|archivedate=19 July 2020}}</ref><ref name="20min 2008">{{cite news|title=Petric und Rakitic hätten sich nicht für Kroatien entscheiden sollen|newspaper=[[20 minuten]]|language=gsw|date=3 March 2008|last=|url=https://www.20min.ch/sport/fussball/story/15177606|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305005132/https://www.20min.ch/sport/fussball/story/15177606|archivedate=5 March 2008}}</ref> He is a naturalized [[Swiss people|Swiss]]<ref name="UEFA">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=1585563.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609024916/http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=1585563.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 June 2012|title=The official website for European football |website=UEFA|date=6 January 2013|publisher=Union of European Football Associations}}</ref><ref>[http://www.tagesanzeiger.ch/sport/fussball/Die-Berner-denken-zu-oft-ans-Verlieren/story/23554224 Tagesanzeiger.ch: «Die Berner denken zu oft ans Verlieren»:]''Ich bin Schweizer und bosnischer Kroate aus Sarajevo.''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kicker.de/vladimir-petkovic/trainer|title=Trainersteckbrief Vladimir Petkovic, Schweiz}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ilmessaggero.it/sport/sslazio/petkovic_in_testa_solo_la_lazio_il_tecnico_ha_lasciato_la_famiglia_in_svizzera_per_evitare_ogni_distrazione/notizie/219395.shtml Ilmessaggero.it: Petkovic, in testa solo la Lazio Il tecnico ha lasciato la famiglia in Svizzera per evitare ogni distrazione]: ''In realtà, per non rimanere tanto lontani al famoso film dove ci sono due mostri sacri come De Sica e la Lollo (Pane, amore e fantasia ndc), a lui molto caro secondo alcuni amici, in questo uomo croato tutto d’un pezzo c’è tanta fantasia e soprattutto tantissimo amore per la sua famiglia.'' Archived: [https://web.archive.org/web/20121023213332/http://www.ilmessaggero.it/sport/sslazio/petkovic_in_testa_solo_la_lazio_il_tecnico_ha_lasciato_la_famiglia_in_svizzera_per_evitare_ogni_distrazione/notizie/219395.shtml]</ref> and holds [[Bosnia and Herzegovina nationality law|Bosnian]], [[Swiss nationality law|Swiss]] and [[Croatian nationality law|Croatian]] passports.<ref>[https://nzzas.nzz.ch/magazin/wer-ist-vladimir-petkovic-auf-spurensuche-in-sarajevo-ld.1628602 ''Wer ist Vladimir Petkovic? Auf Spurensuche in Sarajevo.''] In: ''[[NZZ am Sonntag]]'', 5. Juni 2021.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lazioland.com/NewsProfile.htm?NewsId=1507&fb_comment_id=277139629074798_1216190|title=The Doctor|date=24 December 2012|access-date=29 June 2021|author=Ali Alkatiri|website=Lazioland}}</ref><ref>[http://www.blick.ch/sport/fussball/superleague/petkovic-wird-neuer-sion-trainer-id1884720.html Petkovic wird neuer Sion-Trainer!]: ''Mit YB wurde der Staatsbürger von Kroatien und der Schweiz zweimal Vize-Meister und verlor 2009 mit den Bernern den Cupfinal - gegen Sion.''</ref> His parents worked in education and due to the family's frequent moving, Petković changed schools several times.<ref name="SB">{{cite web|url=http://www.slobodna-bosna.ba/vijest/1283/mourinho_sa_ilidze.html|title=Mourinho sa Ilidže}}</ref> They first lived in [[Vrelo Bosne]] and then when he was five years old, in [[Hadžići]] near Sarajevo.<ref name="SB"/>

==Playing career==
A midfielder with good technique, Petković started playing football in [[Ilidža]] as an eleven-year-old before joining the youth sector of his hometown side [[FK Sarajevo]] as a fifteen-year-old.<ref name="SB"/>

He remained at FK Sarajevo and began his professional career there<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerodic.com/autor/fudbal_1945-1992/igraci/igraci_p.htm|title=zerodic.com|access-date=9 December 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330182235/http://www.zerodic.com/autor/fudbal_1945-1992/igraci/igraci_p.htm|archive-date=30 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> in the early 1980s. Petković made only a handful of appearances in a strong Sarajevo side led on the pitch by Bosnian [[Safet Sušić]].<ref name="SB"/> Petković was a part of the Sarajevo side that won the [[1984–85 Yugoslav First League]], but made only two league appearances for them.<ref name="UEFA"/> His time at Sarajevo was interrupted by two brief stints elsewhere: first, a successful time with [[FK Rudar Prijedor|Rudar Prijedor]] where Petković showed good scoring ability; and then a less successful season in the [[1985-86 Yugoslav Second League|Yugoslav Second League]] with a poor [[NK Koper]] side which was relegated after finishing last.

Petković emigrated from [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]] in 1987, leaving FK Sarajevo and moving permanently to [[Switzerland]], where he joined second division club [[FC Chur 97|Chur 97]]. After a season with Chur, Petković moved to the Swiss top division, joining a strong [[FC Sion|Sion]] side. Sion achieved a third-place finish in the [[Swiss Super League|Nationalliga]] but Petković left the club at the end of the season after only making six league appearances.

After leaving Sion, Petković moved back into the lower tiers, first joining [[FC Martigny-Sports|Martigny-Sports]] before returning to his first Swiss club, Chur 97. Petković enjoyed a career as a regular goalscoring midfielder in the Swiss second division, which included two more stints at [[AC Bellinzona|Bellinzona]] and [[FC Locarno|Lugano]].

Petković completed his playing career as a player-manager with Bellinzona and [[FC Malcantone Agno|Malcantone Agno]], the latter having later merged with financially stricken Lugano.

==Managerial career==
===Coaching in Switzerland===
After his retirement from playing, Petković became a coach and his first job was player-manager at Bellinzona in 1997. In 2004, he took over the reins at Lugano before returning to Bellinzona for the fourth time in his career, where he led the club to the [[2007–08 Swiss Cup|2008 Swiss Cup]] final, only to lose out to [[FC Basel|Basel]], and promotion to the [[Swiss Super League]]. At the beginning of the [[2008–09 Swiss Super League|2008–09 season]], he was appointed as manager of [[BSC Young Boys|Young Boys]]. After taking charge at the club, Petković installed a [[Formation (association football)#3–4–3|3–4–3]] formation and took the [[Bern]] side to a second-placed league finish. After two more seasons with Young Boys, he was sacked after a 1–1 draw against [[FC Luzern|Luzern]] on 7 May 2011. The club finished in third place in the league behind their rivals [[FC Zürich|Zürich]] and Basel.

===Samsunspor and return to Switzerland===
In 2011, he became the new manager of Turkish side [[Samsunspor]]. He resigned from that position in January 2012 with the club in the relegation zone.<ref name="samsunspor">{{Cite news|url=http://www.ntvspor.net/haber/spor-toto-super-lig/57488/samsunsporda-mesut-bakkal-donemi|title=Samsunspor'da Mesut Bakkal dönemi|publisher=NTVSpor|access-date=27 January 2012|language=tr}}</ref> On 15 May 2012, he was named the new temporary manager of [[FC Sion|Sion]] until the end of the 2011–12 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fc-sion.ch/index.php?r=site/text&id=275&culture=de|title=FC Sion - Vladimir Petkovic ist der neue Trainer des FC Sion}}</ref>

===Lazio===
On 2 June 2012, Petković became the new manager of Italian side [[SS Lazio|Lazio]] in [[Serie A]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1642928.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224183536/http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1642928.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 December 2013|title=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA)|website=FIFA}}</ref> He won the [[Coppa Italia]] with the club in the [[2012–13 SS Lazio season|2012–13 season]], thanks to a 71st minute goal from compatriot [[Senad Lulić]] in the [[2013 Coppa Italia Final|final]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.goal.com/en/match/106534/roma-vs-lazio/report?|title=Roma 0-1 Lazio: Biancocelesti edge dour derby to claim Coppa Italia|date=26 May 2013|work=Goal.com|access-date=6 June 2013 }}</ref>

===Switzerland national team===
[[File:Ser-Swi (8).jpg|thumb|upright|Petković with [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]]]

On 23 December 2013, it was announced that Petković was to succeed [[Ottmar Hitzfeld]] as the manager of the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland national team]] after the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name="Petkovic to succeed Hitzfeld">{{cite web |title=Petkovic to succeed Hitzfeld |website=FIFA | date = 23 December 2013 | url = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=2249668/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140104211509/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=2249668/| url-status = dead| archive-date = 4 January 2014}}</ref> As a result, [[Claudio Lotito]] fired Petković claiming a breach of the contract due to not having been duly informed by Petković about the latter's ongoing negotiations with the [[Swiss Football Association]]. Petković was sacked as Lazio manager on 4 January 2014 and was replaced by [[Edy Reja]], which resulted in a legal dispute concerning the contract termination.

Since his appointment to the national team spot in July 2014, Petković has guided the Swiss to the Round of 16 stages of both the [[UEFA Euro 2016]] and the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], along with the quarter-finals of [[UEFA Euro 2020]]. They also reached the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals]]. At the UEFA Euro 2020, he led Switzerland to defeat [[2018 FIFA World Cup Final|world champions]] [[France national football team|France]] 5–4 on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2020 knockout phase#France vs Switzerland|Round of 16]], after a 3–3 draw, to qualify to the [[UEFA Euro 2020 knockout phase#Switzerland vs Spain|quarter-finals]] of the European Championship for the first time in their history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/match/2024481--france-vs-switzerland/ |title=France 3–3 Switzerland |website=UEFA |date=28 June 2021}}{{dead link|date=March 2025|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

===Bordeaux===
In late July 2021, Petković became the manager of French club [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/article/soccer-euro-2020-sports-ligue-1-world-cup-917a05a96106915beb3e6cecc81eca87 |title=Switzerland coach Vladimir Petkovic leaves to join Bordeaux |website=AP News |date=28 July 2021 }}</ref> In February 2022, he was sacked as the team was struggling in the relegation positions in [[2021–22 Ligue 1|Ligue 1]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20220207-struggling-bordeaux-fire-coach-petkovic |title=Struggling Bordeaux fire coach Petkovic |website=France24 |date=7 February 2022 }}</ref>

===Algeria===
On 29 February 2024, Petković became the head coach of the [[Algeria national football team|Algerian national team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/news/articles/algeria-petkovic-coach |title=Algeria appoint Petkovic as new coach |publisher=FIFA |date=29 February 2024 }}</ref> Later that year, on 6 June, he lost his first competitive match 2–1 at home against [[Guinea national football team|Guinea]] during the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c133775pe32o |title=Egypt & Ghana win but Algeria stunned in qualifying |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2024 }}</ref> Four days later, he achieved his first win in a 2–1 victory over [[Uganda national football team|Uganda]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.in/football/match/_/gameId/687296/algeria-uganda |title=Uganda 1–2 Algeria |publisher=ESPN |date=10 June 2024 }}</ref> On 9 October 2025, Algeria qualified for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Keystone-SDA |title=Vladimir Petkovic's Algeria qualify for the World Cup |url=https://www.bluewin.ch/en/sport/football/vladimir-petkovics-algeria-qualify-for-the-world-cup-2909889.html |publisher=blue news |access-date=10 October 2025 |date=9 October 2025}}</ref>

==Charitable work==
While living in Switzerland, Petković worked for [[Caritas Ticino]], a Catholic relief development and social service organisation, for five years.<ref>[http://www.caritas-ticino.ch/media/rivista/archivio/riv_1202/riv-2012_02_articoli/R2_2012_Petkovic.pdf Caritas-ticino.ch: Auguri a Vladimir Petkovic]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/19639201|title=Tottenham and Lazio united by fondness for former star Gazza|first=James|last=Horncastle|website=BBC|date=19 September 2012|access-date=23 April 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.croatia.ch/sport/sportasi/090109_Vladimir_Petkovic.php|title=Hrvatski sport u Svicarskoj|access-date=22 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103214642/http://www.croatia.ch/sport/sportasi/090109_Vladimir_Petkovic.php|archive-date=3 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>

